Fix a Failing Cypress Component Test

02
On this page
  1. Reading the Keyboard Operability Test
  2. 🛠 Challenge: Fix MegaNav Component Markup so the Keyboard Test Passes
  3. 🛠 Solution: Fixing the MegaNav
    1. Replacing the div with a button
    2. Fixing the aria-expanded attribute

Cypress is similar to what we’ve seen with Jest, and includes a different but familiar API.

In this lesson we’ll read our existing test, then make it pass.

Reading the Keyboard Operability Test

Open up the meganav.test.js file inside of the exercise2-cypress-components directory inside of the workshop repo, which contains our failing test.

At the top of the file we import mount from the React flavor of Cypress, as well as the MegaNav component we’ll be testing.

// inside meganav.test.js

import { mount } from '@cypress/react'
import MegaNav from 'components/meganav'
// inside meganav.test.js

import { mount } from '@cypress/react'
import MegaNav from 'components/meganav'

Describing a test for Cypress looks similar to what we saw with Jest. Using the describe keyword, provide a string to name the test (typically the component being tested), then an arrow function where the tests will be written.

Inside of the describe, the first thing add is a beforeEach that will mount the MegaNav component.

beforeEach is a function bundled by Cypress that does what you might think it does: it calls a function before each test. Calling mount inside of it saves us from duplicating code inside the tests. Check out Cypress’ docs for other useful functions.

describe('MegaNav', () => {
	beforeEach(() => {
		mount(<MegaNav/>)
	})
	...
describe('MegaNav', () => {
	beforeEach(() => {
		mount(<MegaNav/>)
	})
	...

After the beforeEach is the it block that describes the keyboard toggle test that is currently failing:

it('should operate with the keyboard via toggle buttons', () => {
	cy.get('[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().click()

	cy.focused().should('have.attr', 'aria-expanded', 'true')
})
it('should operate with the keyboard via toggle buttons', () => {
	cy.get('[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').focus().click()

	cy.focused().should('have.attr', 'aria-expanded', 'true')
})

IIn the first line of the test, the cy.get() query from Cypress is used to query the element we’re looking for.

Since Cypress lets us use CSS selectors when querying (among other options), we can pass in a CSS selector that will reference the element with a data-testid attribute that has a value of meganav-section1.

If we wanted to be more specific, we could adjust the CSS query to specify that we are only interested with buttons that have that particular attribute.

The CSS selector for that would look like this:

button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]
button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]

After the query is a call to .focus() to focus the element before calling .click().

The test focuses the element before clicking because out of the box, Cypress doesn’t implement real browser events. This has implications for accessibility testing. Later we will look at a tool that brings this support in.

In the second line of the test is an assertion that the focused element should have an attribute of aria-expanded with a value of true.

We know that this test fails because cy.focus() was called on an element that couldn’t be focused:

cy.focus() can only be called on a valid focusable element. Your subject is a: <div class="megamenu-navitem header-main-item" id="megamenu-section1" data-testid="megamenu-section1">Plan Yo...</div>

Let’s make this test pass so we can see what a successful test suite looks like in Cypress Component Testing.

🛠 Challenge: Fix MegaNav Component Markup so the Keyboard Test Passes

Work through the MegaNav component code fixing the issues that cause the keyboard operability test to fail.

Run Cypress Component Testing as you make changes until the UI shows that the test has passed.

If you get stuck, check the answers directory to see the fixed component code.

🛠 Solution: Fixing the MegaNav

The first thing to do is track down where the error is happening.

We’ll do this by reading through the code for the MegaNav component.

The error from Cypress Component Testing shows a div with an id of megamenu-section1 which we can see in our code is being added to a <MegaNavSection> subcomponent.

Checking the MegaNavSection code, we can see the id prop is in turn passed into a <SubNavButton> component.

Replacing the div with a button

Inside of the SubNavButton is where the div is. Since we know that a div is not focusable or operable, we’ll change it to a button.

After this update, Cypress Component Testing runs the test again. We still have a failing test, but the error has changed.

Now the error is that it can’t find the aria-expanded attribute.

The Cypress UI lets us step backward through the actions it took in the test. In the screenshot below, a red dot is added to the place where it clicked the button:

Fixing the aria-expanded attribute

Inside of the SubNavButton is where we should add the aria-expanded property.

But since the button itself doesn’t know if the menu is expanded or not, the value will need to be passed in as a prop.

We also should set aria-haspopup to be true, because the button toggles a menu to be opened.

Going back up a level to the MegaNavSection, we can see that it is already sending an aria-expanded prop into the SubNavButton, so that’s taken care of for us. Jumping back to the SubNavButton, we can set the value to props['aria-expanded'].

Here’s what the changes to the SubNavButton look like:

// inside SubNavButton
<button
	aria-expanded={props['aria-expanded']}
	aria-haspopup="true"
	...
// inside SubNavButton
<button
	aria-expanded={props['aria-expanded']}
	aria-haspopup="true"
	...

When Cypress Component Testing runs the test again, we see that our test has passed.

The MegaNav component has been rendered, with the first menu opened with focus on the button.

Note: This video demonstrates how React Refs and Ref Forwarding help the MegaNav determine how to set aria-expanded.
